The New-York tribune., January 08, 1919, Page 11, col. 5 reported on the concert:
&quot;The music at Carnegie Hall came from a single violin with a pianoforte accompaniment. Sascha Jacobsen was the performer, and after the youthful artist had played a Fugue by Tartini, in the dress given it by Fritz Kreisler, the hall buzzed with laudatory comments. Mr. Jacobsen has now played in public often enough to be associated in the public mind with the young geniuses who have come from Russia in the course of the last five years, but last night he established his right to be associated with some of the best of them. He is artistically a product of New York, a pupil of Mr. Kneisel. He draws a tine, full, musical tone from his instrument and a sound, virile appreciation of beauty speaks out of every thing that he does. Besides the Tartini Fugue. he played a Corelli Sonata, which disclosed the firm foundation of his musicianship; the Mendelssohn concerto and a group of short pieces, sentimental and brilliant, to gratify the taste of the multitude.&quot;
