This photo, rendered as a drawing, accompanies the following in the  August, 1918 number of Brooms, Brushes and Mops magazine:

&quot;SERGT EUDELL MILLER LUSHER

Sergt Eudell Miller Lusher was killed in action in France. Sergeant Lusher was 20 years old and was graduated from the Westport High school, Kansas City Mo.  He was refused a commission in the first officers training camp on account of his youth, but remained in the army and went to France with a regiment of regulars to which he had been transferred at his own request in order to get into action without delay.  He was associated with the Opie Brush Co until his enlistment. Mr Lusher has spent his vacations from childhood learning the brush business.  During the year from his graduation until his enlistment he served in the capacity of sales manager for the firm.  He had a wide acquaintance and a host of friends. He was a boy of winning personality and a great future was predicted for him. The one thought which sustains his many friends is that he laid down his life on the Altar of Supreme Sacrifice. He was a brother of Mrs John T Opie,  4001 East Sixty eighth street,  and of Mrs George E Mason,  2735 Robert Gillham Road,  Kansas Mo. He also leaves two other brothers Leo Lusher, Wichita Kansas,  and Orlando Lusher St Joseph Mo.&quot;

